{
  "doc_id": "55334",
  "text": "In V. velutina, the antennal lobe contains approximately the same number of olfactory glomeruli in gynes (269) and workers (265), but significantly fewer in males (247) [CITATION_1] . However, given that workers and drones had learning curves that were not significantly different ( Fig. 2A) , glomeruli differences are unlikely to explain our results. Instead, caste-specific differences in how learning and memory are formed may play a role. [CITATION_2] demonstrated that transcription and translation inhibitors fed to parasitic wasps (Cotesia glomerata and Cotesia rubecula) could interfere with long-term memory (LTM) formation of odours associated with oviposition. Protein synthesis is also likely to be important for LTM and long-lasting memory formation in V. velutina. DNA methylation may also play a role in wasp and hornet memory, as it does for honey bees [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , but this remains to be determined.",
